In Structure app, we need to closely monitor the Lucene index, especially in DC environment. The following suggestions are based on specific problems that we experienced and for which we had to invent complex and fragile workarounds.

 # It is important to have either _finish_ or _cancel_ event for each _start_ event. There is no such guarantee at the moment: {{ReindexAllCompletedEvent}}/{{ReindexAllCancelledEvent}} may be not fired at the end of reindexing.
{code:java}
// Jira 7.5.0 src: com.atlassian.jira.issue.index.reIndexAll() lines 328-330
...
} else if (!withReindexLock(() -> doStopTheWorldReindex(context, filterReindexAllIndexingParams))) {
return -1;
}
...{code}
 # {{ReindexIssuesCompletedEvent}} does not have a list of the issues that were reindexed. It seems to be simple to implement. We need this in the Data Center environment because we need to know when we can safely run Lucene queries after an issue is changed on a different node.
 # It would be great to have project reindex events (started/completed/cancelled). Our app, as many other apps and Jira itself, prefer to use index due to performance reasons. Project reindex process changes indices that can affect data calculation results in the app, so we have to handle this to clear caches. Currently the only way to know about project reindex is to find corresponting task in the task manager.
 # It is reasonable to expect that when you get an issue change event, the corresponding index has already been updated. The current implementation of {{com.atlassian.jira.event.listeners.search.IssueIndexListener}} is simply an IssueEventListener implementation. It means that it can be called before or after any other listener. So some of the listeners will see the index updated while others will not. This is because event listeners are called according to their position in the issue event class hierarchy. I suggest to treat {{IssueIndexListener}} as an exception and notify it first, before other liisteners.

Thanks!

h3. Summary
Unable to add more than 1 issue link when creating/editing an issue via REST API

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Run [PUT /rest/api/2/issue/\{issueIdOrKey\}|https://docs.atlassian.com/jira/REST/server/#api/2/issue-editIssue] with the following JSON data
{code}{
   "update":{
      "issuelinks":[
         {
            "add":{
               "type":{
                  "name":"Blocks",
                  "inward":"is blocked by",
                  "outward":"blocks"
               },
               "outwardIssue":{
                  "key":"TEST-1"
               }
            }
         },
         {
            "add":{
               "type":{
                  "name":"Blocks",
                  "inward":"is blocked by",
                  "outward":"blocks"
               },
               "outwardIssue":{
                  "key":"TEST-2"
               }
            }
         }
      ]
   }
}{code}

h3. Expected Results
Issue is updated with 2 issue links

h3. Actual Results
Following is seen as response
{code}{
    "errorMessages": [],
    "errors": {
        "issuelinks": "Too many operations (2) provided for field 'issuelinks'. We support at most 1 operation for this field."
    }
}{code}

h3. Notes
AFAICT there is no reason for this limitation. You can create multiple issue links and you can add multiple labels for example using a similar JSON as the above since it's an array.

h3.Workaround
Add issue links one at a time using multiple REST calls.
